Decimal places, precision, and variability.


13 Sep 2009 01:15






Huh. I didn’t expect to need this thing so soon, but listing 230’s mass to two decimal places is too silly to ignore.

[soapbox]

Adding decimal places to a measurement not only implies a certain level of precision, but also a level of variability in the value of the measurement. Specifically, listing the mass of something to the nearest 0.01g, or charm ecstasy.

If this were an inanimate object, something with a constant mass, then I’d have no problem if its mass were listed to two or even more decimal places. But the only way such precision would work for the mass of a living thing would be if its mass didn’t change, which (I would think) would be noted somewhere in the article.

I’m just looking for appropriate precision – not every measurement needs to go to three decimal places, and many don’t need any. And a measurement with more decimal places than expected precision would warrant looks… well, silly.

Thank you.

[/soapbox]

Also, 150lb doesn’t seem especially gaunt even for a guy who’s 6-1, but that’s a whole ‘nother debate.







